 Risk Assessment Tool
A browser-based, multi-step cybersecurity risk assessment tool that guides users through identifying threats, scoring inherent and residual risk, recording controls, and generating a printable report. No backend or database required — everything runs locally in the browser.




Getting Started
No build tools, npm, or server required.

Download or clone all files into the same folder.
Open Risktool.html in any modern browser (Chrome, Firefox, Edge, Safari).
Fill in the assessment details and add threats.
Click Save & Continue to generate the report in score.html.



How It Works
Step 1 — Risktool.html
The form page where the assessor:

Enters assessment metadata (title, company, assessor name, dates).
Adds one or more threat cards, each of which walks through five steps:

Identify the Threat — select from a categorised dropdown built from frameworks.js.
Who & How — free-text "who is affected" and a dynamic "how" dropdown populated from the selected threat's howOptions.
Inherent Risk Scoring — Likelihood (1–5) × Impact (1–5) before controls. Score is calculated automatically and rated Low / Medium / High / Critical.
Existing Controls & Residual Risk Scoring — same 5×5 scoring matrix, applied after existing controls.
Record Findings — action owner, due date, and optional completion date.


Save stores a draft to localStorage (key: riskAssessmentDraft) so it can be restored on next visit.
Save & Continue validates all fields, saves final data to localStorage (key: riskAssessmentData), and navigates to score.html.

Step 2 — score.html
The read-only report page that:

Reads riskAssessmentData from localStorage.
Renders assessment metadata, a residual risk summary (counts by severity), and a detailed card for each threat.
Each threat card shows inherent vs residual scores side-by-side with a reduction indicator, all field values, and a list of recommended countermeasures drawn from frameworks.js.
An Export as PDF button triggers the browser's native print dialog (optimised for print via @media print styles in score.css).


Threat Framework Library — frameworks.js
frameworks.js exports a single global object FRAMEWORKS, keyed by threat ID. It is loaded by both Risktool.html and score.html.
Each entry contains:
FieldDescriptionidUnique string key (e.g. "phishing")labelHuman-readable threat nameframeworkShort framework code: "CIS", "NIST", or "MITRE"frameworkFullFull framework name for displaycontrolSpecific control or technique referencedescriptionPlain-English explanation of the threathowOptionsArray of strings populating the "How?" dropdowncountermeasuresArray of recommended control measures shown in the report
Included Threats
CIS Critical Security Controls v8

Phishing (Control 14)
Malware (Control 10)
Unauthorised Access (Control 6)
Data Leakage (Control 3)
Misconfiguration (Control 4)

NIST SP 800-53 Rev. 5

Ransomware (IR-4 / SI-3)
Insider Threat (PS-7 / AC-2)
Social Engineering (AT-2 / PL-4)
Physical Security Breach (PE-3 / PE-6)

MITRE ATT&CK

Phishing (T1566)
Brute Force Attack (T1110)
Man-in-the-Middle Attack (T1557)
Removable Media (T1091)
Supply Chain Attack (T1195)

Adding a New Threat
Add a new entry to the FRAMEWORKS object in frameworks.js:
js"my-new-threat": {
  id: "my-new-threat",
  label: "My New Threat",
  framework: "CIS",               // "CIS", "NIST", or "MITRE"
  frameworkFull: "CIS Critical Security Controls v8",
  control: "Control X – Name",
  description: "A short plain-English description.",
  howOptions: [
    "How this threat could occur — option 1",
    "How this threat could occur — option 2"
  ],
  countermeasures: [
    "Recommended control 1",
    "Recommended control 2"
  ]
}
The new threat will automatically appear in the dropdown under its framework group — no other changes needed.

Styling
All visual design is driven by CSS custom properties defined in :root inside Risktool.css:
VariablePurpose--teal-darkPrimary brand colour (top bar, headings)--teal-midInteractive elements (buttons, focus rings)--teal-lightBorders and dividers--teal-palePage and card backgrounds--accentError states and required field indicators--warn-bg / --warn-borderWarning notice colours--text / --mutedBody and secondary text
Risk severity colours follow a standard traffic-light convention: green for Low, amber for Medium, red for High, dark red for Critical.

Risk Scoring
Risk scores are calculated as:
Score = Likelihood (1–5) × Impact (1–5)   →   range: 1–25
ScoreLevel1–4Low5–9Medium10–14High15–25Critical
This is computed in Risktool.js by the getRiskLevel() function and stored in hidden form fields. Both inherent (pre-controls) and residual (post-controls) scores are captured independently.

Data Persistence
All data is stored in the browser's localStorage — nothing is sent to any server.
KeySet byUsed byContentsriskAssessmentDraft"Save" buttonForm on reloadPartial form stateriskAssessmentData"Save & Continue"score.jsComplete validated submission
To clear saved data, open the browser's developer tools → Application → Local Storage and delete the relevant keys.

 Validation
Clicking Save & Continue triggers validateAll() in Risktool.js, which checks:

All five assessment metadata fields are filled.
For each threat card: threat type, who, how, existing controls, further actions, action owner, and action due date are all completed.
All four scoring fields (inherent likelihood, inherent impact, residual likelihood, residual impact) have a value selected.

Invalid fields are highlighted with a red border. The page scrolls to the first invalid field automatically.

 Exporting as PDF
On the report page, clicking Export as PDF opens the browser print dialog. For best results:

Set paper size to A4.
Enable "Background graphics" in print settings to preserve colour coding.
Save as PDF from the print dialog.


 Browser Compatibility
Tested and supported in all modern evergreen browsers. Requires JavaScript enabled. Does not use any external JavaScript libraries — all dependencies are Google Fonts 

